{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505361"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2434"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2434"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.72,0.09,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19890"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4554"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/34979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old primigravida woman, at 9 weeks gestation, presents to the hospital three hours after the onset of vaginal bleeding and abdominal pain. She reports bleeding several large clots associated with cramping lower abdominal pain. Her pain was 7/10 in intensity but now as reduced to 3/10, and she has no current active bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears worried. Her vital signs are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemperature 37.1\u2103\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart rate 100/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood pressure 110/80 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory rate 16/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen saturation at 98% on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPelvic examination revealed traces of blood and clots surrounding her vagina, on speculum the cervix is closed and there is no active vaginal bleeding. Pelvic ultrasound shows a small amount of fluid in the endometrium and an absent gestational sac with no adnexal masses or free fluid in the abdomen. There are no suggestive findings of an ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Missed miscarriage","Complete miscarriage","Incomplete miscarriage","Threatened miscarriage","Inevitable miscarriage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with crampy abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding/discharge which supports the diagnosis of miscarriage. The improvement of abdominal pain after vaginal bleeding/discharge could indicate that the spontaneous passage of tissue has relieved the pain. A pelvic ultrasound is necessary to ascertain the status and diagnosis of miscarriage as well as rule out an ectopic pregnancy which must be a differential in a woman with pain, bleeding and ultrasound findings of an empty uterus. In this patient, the cervical os is closed and her uterus is empty \u2013 this would suggest a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E and passage of tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMissed miscarriage is defined as pregnancy loss with minimal to no symptoms. The cervical os will also be closed and there will be an empty gestational sac or no fetal cardiac activity in a missed miscarriage. This patient noted the passage of tissue with painful bleeding which is not in keeping with a missed miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn incomplete miscarriage would present similarly to a complete miscarriage. However, the cervical os often remains open and there would be remnants of tissue within the uterus. Ultrasound may also reveal an empty uterus depending on how much tissue remains in the uterus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThreatened miscarriage presents with vaginal bleeding and a closed cervical os. The ultrasound would reveal a live intrauterine pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn inevitable miscarriage is similar to a threatened miscarriage, however, the cervical os is open indicating that a miscarriage is imminent. A fetal heart rate (FHR) may or may not be present on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An empty gestational sac is indicative of a complete miscarriage."],"references":["Clement EG, Horvath S, McAllister A, et al. The Language of First-Trimester Nonviable Pregnancy: Patient-Reported Preferences and Clarity. Obstet Gynecol 2019; 133:149.","Kolte AM, Bernardi LA, Christiansen OB, et al. Terminology for pregnancy loss prior to viability: a consensus statement from the ESHRE early pregnancy special interest group. Hum Reprod 2015; 30:495."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19890"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2434"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19890"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-04-14T16:40:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-04-14T16:40:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"i